t":1,"highlight_end":75},{"text":"//!","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":4},{"text":"//! **Does this crate support `no_std`?**","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":42},{"text":"//!","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":4},{"text":"//! Yes, but with caveats. `OnceCell` is a synchronization primitive which","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":75},{"text":"//! _semantically_ relies on blocking. `OnceCell` guarantees that at most one","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":78},{"text":"//! `f` will be called to compute the value. If two threads of execution call","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":78},{"text":"//! `get_or_init` concurrently, one of them has to wait.","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":57},{"text":"//!","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":4},{"text":"//! Waiting fundamentally requires OS support. Execution environment needs to","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":78},{"text":"//! understand who waits on whom to prevent deadlocks due to priority inversion.","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":81},{"text":"//! You _could_ make code to compile by blindly using pure spinlocks, but the","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":78},{"text":"//! runtime behavior would be subtly wrong.","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":44},{"text":"//!","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":4},{"text":"//! Given these constraints, `once_cell` provides the following options:","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":73},{"text":"//!","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":4},{"text":"//! - The `race` module provides similar, but distinct synchronization primitive","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":81},{"text":"//!   which is compatible with `no_std`. With `race`, the `f` function can be","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":78},{"text":"//!   called multiple times by different threads, but only one thread will win","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":79},{"text":"//!   to install the value.","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":28},{"text":"//! - `critical-section` feature (with a `-`, not `